<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED-mail regrets the inadvertent delay in posting this report.
The following background information extracted from the Gideon
database <http://www.gideononline.com/promed> was posted as part of
ProMED-mail post: "Lassa fever - Sierra Leone (Kenema) (02):
background 20040421.1110".
Lassa fever is most common in the eastern region; one to 4 _Mastomys_
[small, mouse-like African rodents] are found in every household in
this area, of which 1-20 percent are infected with Lassa virus. In
some areas of eastern Sierra Leone, the disease accounts for 30
percent of medical death in-hospital, 30 percent of deafness, and 70
percent of spontaneous abortion. 8-52 percent of the population are
seropositive.
Notable outbreaks:
------------------
1970 to 1972 - 63 cases were reported in Panguma-Tongo region
(Eastern Province) during October 1970 to October 1972.
1995 - An outbreak (167 cases, 60 fatal) was reported in Kenema
District -- most patients were adolescent females.
1996 - 799 cases (148 fatal) were reported, including 99 cases (13
fatal) from Kenema District during November and December.
1997 - 353 (43 fatal) cases were reported during January to April 1997.
2003 - An outbreak of suspected Lassa fever (80 cases, 8 fatal) was
reported in the central region, with several cases reported in
refugee camps.
2004 - An outbreak was reported in Kenema district. - Mod.CP]
